  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>While other families ate ice cream, Ivan Frantz's children ate ice milk. While other families cooked with butter, his family used margarine. Frantz was a cardiologist at the University of Minnesota who believed, with the certainty of a man who had organized his life around an idea, that saturated fat was killing Americans. He had designed the largest dietary fat trial in human history to prove it.</p>
  <p>Starting in 1968, he randomized more than 9,000 patients — residents of state mental hospitals and nursing homes, whose meals his team controlled directly — into two groups. One ate the standard American diet, high in animal fat. The other had that fat replaced with corn oil, rich in linoleic acid. For up to four and a half years, researchers tracked both groups.</p>
  <p>The cholesterol numbers were textbook. The corn oil group fell nearly 14 percent, precisely as predicted. Then the death rates came in.</p>
  <p>The corn oil group was dying faster.</p>
  <p>Frantz never published the full results. A sparse paper appeared in 1989 — fifteen years after the trial ended — silent on the mortality finding, thin on data. He died in 2009. When a researcher at the NIH named Christopher Ramsden heard about the experiment and wondered if the full data still existed, he contacted Frantz's sons. One of them, Dr. Robert Frantz, a cardiologist at the Mayo Clinic, drove to his childhood home and searched the basement. On his third trip, in a far corner, he found unlabeled cardboard boxes. Inside: ancient magnetic computer tapes, sheaves of yellowed paper, 9,423 patient records.</p>
  <p>The full re-analysis appeared in the <em>BMJ</em> in 2016. Forty-three years after the trial ended.</p>
</section>

<section id="aha-crisco" class="reveal">
  <h2>The AHA Was Born on Crisco's Dime</h2>
  <p>In 1948, the American Heart Association was a small gathering of cardiologists with a large mission and almost no money. Then Procter &amp; Gamble, maker of Crisco vegetable shortening, ran a radio contest and designated the proceeds — $1.7 million, worth roughly $20 million today — to the AHA. The organization, in the words of its own promotional materials, received the "bang of big bucks" that "launched" it as a national force. Procter &amp; Gamble made a hydrogenated vegetable oil. The organization it funded would soon recommend that Americans replace butter and lard with products like it.</p>
  <p>No document proves that P&amp;G purchased two generations of dietary policy. But the relationship between the AHA and the industries that profit from seed oil consumption has never been fully resolved, and the public is rarely told this when consulting the organization's guidelines.</p>
  <p>The funding flows forward in time, not just backward. Bayer — owner of LibertyLink soybeans, a primary source of the soybean oil that constitutes most "vegetable oil" consumed in the United States — has pledged up to $500,000 to the AHA. The landmark 2017 meta-analysis in <em>The Lancet Diabetes &amp; Endocrinology</em>, widely cited in support of linoleic acid's health benefits, was funded by Unilever, one of the world's largest manufacturers of products made with seed oils—and Unilever's funding extended to at least one author's institution, creating potential conflicts beyond the disclosure. The study found that higher tissue concentrations of linoleic acid were associated with lower type 2 diabetes risk — a genuine finding, published in a credible journal (citation unverified). The funding disclosure is in the fine print.</p>
  <p>This doesn't automatically invalidate the studies, but it demands scrutiny: industry-funded research often aligns with sponsors' interests, as evidenced by historical patterns in nutrition science. What it establishes is that the evidence base for the AHA's core recommendation — replace saturated fat with polyunsaturated fat — has a funding architecture the public has not been clearly shown, and that architecture runs in a single direction.</p>
</section>

<section id="advisory-five-trials" class="reveal">
  <h2>An Advisory Built on Five Trials, Minus One</h2>
  <p>In 2017, the AHA published a Presidential Advisory in <em>Circulation</em> — the most authoritative document the organization produces — recommending that Americans replace saturated fats with polyunsaturated vegetable oils to reduce cardiovascular disease by approximately 30 percent, "similar to the reduction achieved by statin treatment." The advisory was methodologically selective by design: it included only randomized controlled trials in which saturated fat was specifically replaced with polyunsaturated fat, not with carbohydrates. This is a defensible choice; replacing one macronutrient with another tests a specific question.</p>
  <p>There have been exactly five such trials in human history. The Minnesota Coronary Experiment was one of them.</p>
  <p>The advisory acknowledged the MCE and noted its limitations: severe participant attrition, an institutionalized population, a linoleic acid intake (13 percent of calories) far exceeding current dietary recommendations. Fair. But the framing quietly converted "the largest dietary fat trial ever conducted showed no mortality benefit" into "methodological limitations preclude a clear conclusion." The 2017 advisory's headline finding — a 30 percent reduction in cardiovascular disease — was drawn from the other four trials, which showed cholesterol-lowering effects that the AHA treated as near-conclusive evidence of cardiovascular protection.</p>
  <p>This is where the reasoning becomes circular. Cholesterol reduction is a surrogate endpoint. It measures a number in the blood. It is not the same as not dying. The MCE had demonstrated this distinction in 9,423 people over four and a half years. A lower cholesterol level correlated, in that trial, with a <em>higher</em> risk of dying. The 2017 advisory used surrogate endpoint evidence to claim a clinical benefit that its own most rigorous trial had failed to confirm.</p>
</section>

<section id="cholesterol-fell" class="reveal">
  <h2>Cholesterol Fell. Death Rates Rose Anyway.</h2>
  <p>The recovered MCE data, once analyzed, showed this: for every 30-milligram-per-deciliter drop in total cholesterol, the risk of dying increased by 22 percent. The corn oil group did not have less atherosclerosis. They did not have fewer heart attacks. They died faster — a finding driven primarily by participants over 65, though the overall mortality curve ran in the same direction for the full cohort.</p>
  <p>When journalist Gary Taubes asked Ivan Frantz, before his death, why the full results had taken sixteen years to publish and why the mortality data had gone unreported even then, Frantz's answer was: "We were just disappointed in the way it came out." This is not the language of fraud. It is something more familiar: a scientist whose life's work depended on a hypothesis that his own most rigorous trial had failed to support, and who could not bring himself to publish that failure cleanly.</p>
  <p>The MCE was not alone. In 2013, Ramsden recovered another long-lost randomized trial, the Sydney Diet Heart Study of the 1960s, whose full data had similarly been preserved on old magnetic tapes and never fully published. Reanalyzing it, he found the same pattern: participants who replaced saturated fat with polyunsaturated fat high in linoleic acid had higher rates of death from coronary heart disease than the control group. When Ramsden pooled the results of all five available controlled trials, the summary finding was consistent: substituting linoleic-acid-rich vegetable oils for saturated fat reliably lowers cholesterol. It does not reliably lower cardiovascular mortality.</p>

  <div class="data-callout reveal">
    <p><strong>On the MCE's Limitations</strong></p>
    <p>The Minnesota Coronary Experiment has genuine methodological constraints that prevent treating its findings as definitive. Attrition was severe — more than 83 percent of participants did not complete the full intervention period. The study population was institutionalized and unrepresentative of the general public. The linoleic acid content of the intervention diet (13 percent of calories) far exceeds both current dietary recommendations and typical real-world consumption. The mortality signal was driven largely by participants over 65. These are not dismissible caveats. What the trial cannot be made to show, despite all of them, is evidence of benefit from the intervention. The MCE does not establish that seed oils cause harm. It establishes that replacing saturated fat with corn oil produced no measurable mortality benefit. Those are different findings, and only one of them is in the data.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="nia-researcher" class="reveal">
  <h2>The NIH Researcher the AHA Didn't Answer</h2>
  <p>Christopher Ramsden works within the intramural programs of the National Institute on Aging and the National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism at the NIH. He is not a podcaster, not affiliated with any supplement company, not selling anything. He has spent his career on the biochemistry of linoleic acid and what happens to it inside the body.</p>
  <p>Linoleic acid is chemically unstable. When it oxidizes — during cooking, during industrial processing, or through normal cellular metabolism — it produces a class of compounds called oxidized linoleic acid metabolites, or OXLAMs: specifically 9-HODE, 13-HODE, and related compounds. Ramsden's group has shown in human subjects that lowering dietary linoleic acid reduces the plasma concentration of these metabolites. That is a measurable, repeatable finding in humans. OXLAMs are elevated in patients with Alzheimer's dementia and with nonalcoholic steatohepatitis; their concentrations correlate with severity of both conditions. A 2018 paper in <em>BMJ Open Heart</em> — by independent researchers with no declared funding — proposed that the primary driver of atherosclerosis is not LDL cholesterol per se, but the oxidation of linoleic acid within LDL particles, which renders them unrecognizable to normal cellular receptors and initiates foam cell formation and plaque.</p>
  <p>The AHA's published position is that there is no credible evidence that linoleic acid promotes inflammation in humans at dietary levels.</p>
  <p>These two positions don't simply contradict each other. They describe different things. Ramsden's research is real, NIH-funded, and published in peer-reviewed journals. It is also predominantly conducted in animal models and in patients with pre-existing disease. Moving from "OXLAMs are elevated in Alzheimer's patients" to "dietary seed oils cause neurodegeneration" requires several inferential steps the data have not taken. The mechanism is biologically plausible. The human evidence is preliminary. The research is not fringe. It is inconvenient, and it has not generated the large-scale human trials needed to resolve it.</p>
  <p>Americans now consume approximately 7 percent of their daily calories as linoleic acid, compared to an estimated 2 to 3 percent a century ago. Linoleic acid is genuinely essential — the body cannot synthesize it, and it is required for cell membrane function and other basic biological processes. But essentiality at low doses does not establish safety at high doses. Oxygen is essential. The argument that a nutrient's essentiality proves the safety of consuming it at ten times historical levels is not an argument; it is a category error that has been doing significant work in the seed oil debate without anyone naming it.</p>

  <aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The cholesterol fell exactly as predicted. For every 30 mg/dL it dropped, the risk of dying rose 22 percent. When asked why the full data had gone unpublished for fifteen years, Frantz said: 'We were just disappointed in the way it came out.'"</p></aside>
</section>

<section id="seeds-dont-arrive-alone" class="reveal">
  <h2>Seed Oils Don't Arrive Alone</h2>
  <p>The observational evidence in favor of seed oils has a structural problem: it cannot isolate them. Most Americans consume seed oils primarily through ultra-processed foods — fast food fryers, packaged snacks, commercially baked goods, bottled dressings. These products do not contain seed oil alone. They contain refined flour, added sugar, sodium, emulsifiers, and, where heat is involved, exactly the kind of lipid oxidation products the OXLAM hypothesis worries about. A study that finds "higher seed oil intake is associated with lower cardiovascular risk" in a large observational cohort is also, inescapably, finding something about the kinds of people who follow dietary guidelines: they tend to exercise, not smoke, and see a doctor. The association may be tracking behavior, not biochemistry.</p>
  <p>This is the gap the online seed oil discourse identified and then drove straight past. The "seed oil disrespecters" — the carnivore-diet corner of the internet that treats canola oil as a slow poison — found a real funding problem and a real evidentiary gap, then sprinted to conclusions the data don't support. Their certainty has made the legitimate scientific questions harder to discuss seriously, because every serious inquiry now risks being mistaken for a podcast segment.</p>
  <p>The real story is less dramatic and more durable. Ultra-processed food is almost certainly harmful, for reasons that involve seed oils, refined carbohydrates, and industrial processing in combinations that current nutrition research cannot cleanly disentangle. Randomized trial evidence for seed oil benefit is thinner than most people have been told. The mechanism for potential harm at high doses is being investigated by Ramsden's group at the NIH and has received less attention than the question warrants. The organizations best positioned to fund the definitive human trials have a financial interest in the current guidelines remaining unchanged.</p>
</section>

<section id="how-many-boxes" class="reveal">
  <h2>How Many Other Boxes Are There</h2>
  <p>Robert Frantz drove to his childhood home three times before he found the boxes. They were unlabeled, pushed to a far corner of the basement — the accumulated records of the largest dietary fat trial in human history, showing that the intervention it tested produced no mortality benefit. His father had raised his children on margarine and ice milk instead of butter and ice cream, genuinely believing that saturated fat was killing Americans. His trial had told him he was wrong. He was, by his own account, "disappointed in the way it came out."</p>
  <p>There is no evidence that Ivan Frantz suppressed his data in bad faith. There is considerable evidence that he was a scientist who could not square what his trial found with what his career required him to believe. The effect on dietary policy was identical to suppression.</p>
  <p>The question the evidence cannot yet answer is whether seed oils, consumed at current levels, are causing meaningful harm. They may be largely neutral, a misidentified culprit in a story whose actual villain is ultra-processed food. They may be contributing, through the OXLAM pathway or through displacement of omega-3 fats in cell membranes, to conditions that take decades to surface. The honest answer? We don't know yet, because the big players with the cash—AHA and its industry backers—haven't bothered to fund the trials that might expose their golden goose as a dud.</p>
  <p>What we do know is this. The evidence base for the AHA's most influential dietary recommendation is built on five randomized controlled trials. Two of the most rigorous — both recovered from old magnetic tapes after spending years unpublished — showed no mortality benefit from the intervention. The organization that issued the recommendation carries significant funding from companies whose products depend on it being believed. A credible NIH researcher has spent years documenting a biological mechanism that could explain the harm the trials hinted at, and no major health body has funded the human trials needed to evaluate it properly.</p>
  <p>This is not a conspiracy. It is a description of how dietary policy gets made: through a negotiation between evidence, funding, and institutional inertia that the public is rarely invited to observe. The guidelines that shape what people eat, what doctors recommend, and what food companies put in their products emerge from this process. They carry institutional authority that outstrips their evidentiary basis.</p>
  <p>Ivan Frantz's full data sat in a box for forty-three years. The question worth carrying out of this is not whether to stop buying canola oil. It's how many other boxes there are — and who decides whether to open them.</p>
</section>

